1.Preparation¶

1.1 Business Understanding¶

This dataset has over 370,000 instances of used cars and 20 features, including both categorical and numerical features. It matches the Lab requirement and is free to download at kaggle.com.

Driving is a common way to go out in the United States. US vehicle registration data shows that about 276.1 million vehicles were registered in 2018. The United States is one of the largest automobile markets around the world. In the overall US automotive market, the used car market is an important component. According to the statistics from statista.com released in March 2018, sales of new car dropped to 17.1 million vehicles while sales of used car climbed to an all-time high of 42.7 million vehicles in 2017. In the used car market, price is always a significant issue for both sellers and buyers because sellers want to sell a car at the highest price while buyers want to buy an ideal used car at the lowest price.

So we decided to use 8 different kinds of price range to help us to explore the features relationship.
(0: price < $\$$2000; 1: $\$$2000 < price < $\$$5000; 2: $\$$5000 < price < $\$$10000; 3: $\$$10000 < price < $\$$15000; 4: $\$$15000 < price < $\$$20000; 5: $\$$20000 < price < $\$$25000; 6: $\$$25000 < price < $\$$30000; 7: $\$$30000 < price. )

Through visualizing the features, exploring the features relationship, and other methods, we are able to help sellers and buyers to understand the most significant issues leading to the price range of used car. From the analyzing, the sellers could have an idea what kind of price range they can sell at to maximize their benefits, and the buyers could have an idea what kind of the best used car they can buy under their budgets. The end goal of analyzing a dataset like this would be to help sellers and buyers to predict the price range of car based on the different features of car they have.

We are trying to used the past data to analysis what features will affect the price range most, or which decided the car's price range. And we split our data to test whether the factors we found are really affect a used car's price range when we do prediction. If the algorithm is learning properly, we expect the difference between the actual price and the predicted price range as small as possible. This may help some websites which are helping value the used cars' price range, like Kelly Blue Book, to predict the cars' value range more accuray. That's what we are trying to achieve in this Lab.

1.3 Cross-Product Features¶

According to our dataset, there are totally eight categorical features that influence the price range: vehicleType, yearOfRegistration, gearbox, model, fuelType, brand, notRepairedDamage, and postalCode. Among these features, we want to focus on vehicleType, gearbox, model, fuelType, brand, and notRepairedDamage. Although yearOfRegistration and postalCode are categorical variables, they are represented by numbers, so we just regard them as numeric variables.

Different brands make the price very different. For example, buying a Porsche usually costs much higher than buying a Nissan. Also, when we choose different model among a same brand, the price can be different. Choosing a car in a top-level series needs more money than choosing a car in a bottom-level series. So we combine brand and model into one cross-product feature. Among a same brand, different types of vehicle also influeces the price. So we combine brand and vehicleType into one cross-product feature. One model of car may offer two different gearbox: automatic and manual. Due to different manufacturing processes and costs,and if a car has an automatic gear, then it's price generally higher than the car which has manual gear. So we combine gearbox and model into one cross-product feature. When we consider the factors that influence the price of the used car, we treat brand, model, vehicleType, and gearbox as internal factors because they are related to the car itself. We treat fuelType and notRepairedDamage as external factors. So we combine fuelType and notRepairedDamage into one cross-product feature.

Therefore,brand X model, brand X vehicleType, gearbox X model, fuelType X notRepairedDamage should be combined into cross-product features.

From the countplot shown above, it is clear that the numbers between each pricerange are unbalanced. Pricerange 1 has the most numbers and pricerange 6 has the least numbers. After comparing with different measure models, we decided to use F1 score. Because F1 score is good at evaluating uneven cases.

F1 scores has macro average and micro average methods. A macro-average will compute the metric independently for each class and then take the average (hence treating all classes equally), whereas a micro-average will aggregate the contributions of all classes to compute the average metric. For our case, it was apparently not equally distributed, so we chose the micro-average method. And from the classification report, we can see that the micro-average methods have higher precision than the macro-average method.

from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer,f1_score

# use f1 micro as our scorer
scorer = make_scorer(score_func=f1_score,
                     pos_label=1,
                     greater_is_better=True,
                     average='micro')

1.5 Data Spliting Selection¶

Because there is significant imbalance in our dataset, stratified k-fold cross validation and stratified shuffle split both are good methods to split data. Stratified means each part preserves the same percentage of samples of each class as the original data. So we are considering about two methods: stratified k-fold and stratified shuffle split.

The stratified k-fold method shuffles data at first, and after that splits the data into n_splits folds and done. Every sample must be in one and only one fold. And it only and always shuffles data one time before splitting, therefore the test sets do not overlap. The stratified shuffle split method randomly samples the entire dataset during each iteration to generate a training set and a testing set. The test_size and train_size parameters control how large the testing and training set set should be for each iteration. Because the stratified shuffle split method shuffles each time before splitting and it splits n_splits times, the test sets can overlap, but it is also possible that some samples are neither in the training set nor the testing set.

As the dataset grows, the cross validation time increases. So, if the dataset is large, the shuffle split method might be better because we can tune the test_size and train_size parameters to take less time. After the data preparation, our dataset still contains 202112 records, which is not a small dataset, so we decide to use the shuffle split method.

In [33]:
# we find f1 score calculation from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43547402/how-to-calculate-f1-macro-in-keras
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit
from keras import backend as K

def f1(y_true, y_pred):
    def recall(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        possible_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1)))
        recall = true_positives / (possible_positives + K.epsilon())
        return recall

    def precision(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        predicted_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_pred, 0, 1)))
        precision = true_positives / (predicted_positives + K.epsilon())
        return precision
    precision = precision(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = recall(y_true, y_pred)
    return 2*((precision*recall)/(precision+recall+K.epsilon()))

acc = 0
for train_index, test_index in cv2.split(X, y):
    X_train, X_test= df_clean.iloc[train_index],df_clean.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test= df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[train_index],df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[test_index]
    
    ohe = OneHotEncoder()
    X_train_ohe = ohe.fit_transform(X_train[categorical_headers_ints].values)
    X_test_ohe = ohe.transform(X_test[categorical_headers_ints].values)

    X_train_num =  X_train[numeric_headers].values
    X_test_num = X_test[numeric_headers].values
    
    from keras.layers import concatenate
    cross_columns = [['brand','model'],
                 ['brand','vehicleType'],
                 ['gearbox','model'],
                 ['fuelType','notRepairedDamage']]

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_wide_branch_outputs = []

    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        # create crossed labels
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append( X_crossed_train )
        X_ints_test.append( X_crossed_test )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# merge the branches together
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []
    # add in the embeddings
    for col in categorical_headers_ints:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # also get a dense branch of the numeric features
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                            sparse=False,
                            name='numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

    model3 = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)
    

    model3.compile(optimizer='adagrad',
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=[f1])
    

# lets also add the history variable to see how we are doing
# and lets add a validation set to keep track of our progress
    history = model3.fit(X_ints_train+ [X_train_num],
                        y_train, 
                        epochs=10, 
                        batch_size=1000, 
                        verbose=1, 
                        validation_data = (X_ints_test + [X_test_num], y_test))

    a = np.sum(history.history['f1'])/10
    acc += a
    print(a)

    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('MSE Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

acc4 = 0
for train_index, test_index in cv2.split(X, y):
    X_train, X_test= df_clean.iloc[train_index],df_clean.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test= df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[train_index],df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[test_index]
    
    ohe = OneHotEncoder()
    X_train_ohe = ohe.fit_transform(X_train[categorical_headers_ints].values)
    X_test_ohe = ohe.transform(X_test[categorical_headers_ints].values)

    X_train_num =  X_train[numeric_headers].values
    X_test_num = X_test[numeric_headers].values
    
    from keras.layers import concatenate
    cross_columns = [['brand','model'],
                 ['brand','vehicleType'],
                 ['gearbox','model'],
                 ['fuelType','notRepairedDamage']]

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_wide_branch_outputs = []

    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        # create crossed labels
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append( X_crossed_train )
        X_ints_test.append( X_crossed_test )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# merge the branches together
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []
    # add in the embeddings
    for col in categorical_headers_ints:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # also get a dense branch of the numeric features
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                            sparse=False,
                            name='numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=60,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep4')(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

    model4 = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)
    
    model4.compile(optimizer='adagrad',
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=[f1])

# lets also add the history variable to see how we are doing
# and lets add a validation set to keep track of our progress
    history = model4.fit(X_ints_train+ [X_train_num],
                    y_train, 
                    epochs=10, 
                    batch_size=1000, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_ints_test + [X_test_num], y_test))
    
    a = np.sum(history.history['f1'])/10
    acc4 += a
    print(a)

    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('MSE Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

acc7 = 0
for train_index, test_index in cv2.split(X, y):
    X_train, X_test= df_clean.iloc[train_index],df_clean.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test= df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[train_index],df_clean['pricerange'].iloc[test_index]
    
    ohe = OneHotEncoder()
    X_train_ohe = ohe.fit_transform(X_train[categorical_headers_ints].values)
    X_test_ohe = ohe.transform(X_test[categorical_headers_ints].values)

    X_train_num =  X_train[numeric_headers].values
    X_test_num = X_test[numeric_headers].values
    
    from keras.layers import concatenate
    cross_columns = [['brand','model'],
                 ['brand','vehicleType'],
                 ['gearbox','model'],
                 ['fuelType','notRepairedDamage']]

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_wide_branch_outputs = []

    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed columns as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        # create crossed labels
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values,  X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append( X_crossed_train )
        X_ints_test.append( X_crossed_test )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name = '_'.join(cols)+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_wide_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# merge the branches together
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []
    # add in the embeddings
    for col in categorical_headers_ints:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )

        # get the number of categories
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1) # same as the max(df_train[col])

        # create embedding branch from the number of categories
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # also get a dense branch of the numeric features
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],),
                            sparse=False,
                            name='numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append( x )

    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=70,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=35,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep4')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=20,activation='relu', name='deep5')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=15,activation='relu', name='deep6')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep7')(deep_branch)





    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',name='combined')(final_branch)

    model7 = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch)
    
    model7.compile(optimizer='adagrad',
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=[f1])

# lets also add the history variable to see how we are doing
# and lets add a validation set to keep track of our progress
    history = model7.fit(X_ints_train+ [X_train_num],
                    y_train, 
                    epochs=10, 
                    batch_size=1000, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_ints_test + [X_test_num], y_test))
    
    a = np.sum(history.history['f1'])/10
    acc7 += a
    print(a)

    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['f1'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_f1'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('MSE Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
from scipy import interp
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit
ssf = cv2.split(X_train,y_train)

mean_tpr = 0.0
mean_fpr = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
all_tpr = []

for i, (train, test) in enumerate(ssf):
    probas = pipe_lr.fit(X_train[train],
                         y_train[train]).predict_proba(X_train[test])

    perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
    roc_auc = 0
    classes = np.unique(y_train[train])
    # get the mean fpr and tpr, per class
    for j in classes:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train[test],
                                         probas[:, j],
                                         pos_label=j)
        perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
        perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
        roc_auc += auc(fpr, tpr)
        
    perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
    roc_auc /= len(classes)
    mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr
    plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'--',lw=1,label='Mean Class ROC fold %d (area = %0.2f)'
                   % (i+1, roc_auc))
    
mean_tpr /= 10
mean_auc = auc(mean_fpr, mean_tpr)
plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'k-',lw=2,label='Total Mean ROC (area = %0.2f)'
                   % (mean_auc))
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

The total mean ROC for MLP is 0.89, as we can see above, the best average accuracy of Wide and Deep learning is 0.934219, from the 7 layers wide and deep learning model, so for this situation , we will say that Wide and Deep Learning model performance better for our dataset.

3 Exceptional Work¶

There are 11 variables in our dataset, which means that a lot of features need to be explored and understood.T-sne is very suitable for high-dimension datasets so we choose to do the t-sne here and calculate the probabilities of similar observations in the low-dimentional dataset. What's more, from the embedding weights in deep network, we could get the information that most the relationships between them are not linear and t-SNE is good at capturing non-linear dependencies.

In [52]:
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
#from umap import UMAP
from keras.layers import Input, Embedding, Dot, Reshape, Dense
from keras.models import Model

Since from the previous part, we can get that when wide and deep model has 7 layers, it has the best performance, so we choose the 7 layers model to do our work. Since we chosed these four cross product features:brand X model, brand X vehicleType, gearbox X model, fuelType X notRepairedDamage at the very beginning, so there are four embeds about them in our model. We decided to use T-sne to perform these four embeds dimensionality reduction in order to visualize results.
